:'''''Natural Supernaturalism''' can also refer to the book of [[literary criticism]] by [[M. H. Abrams]].''

'''Natural Supernaturalism''' is the name of a chapter in [[Thomas Carlyle]]'s novel [[Sartor Resartus]], which, says Dr. Stirling, "contains the very first word of a higher [[philosophy]] as yet spoken in [[Great Britain]], the very first [[English language|English]] word towards the restoration and rehabilitation of the dethroned Upper Powers."{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

The [[Nuttall Encyclopaedia]] states that Natural Supernaturalism refers to the [[supernatural]] found latent in the natural, and manifesting itself in it, or of the [[miracle|miraculous]] in the common and everyday course of things.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

Carlyle's theory of Natural Supernaturalism influenced [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]] and [[Henry David Thoreau]], two admirers of Carlyle.  It therefore contributed greatly to [[American Transcendentalism]].

