{{nihongo|'''Sadayoshi Fukuda'''|福田 定良|Fukuda Sadayoshi|April 6, 1917 &ndash; December 12, 2002}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] social philosopher and critic.
==Biography== Fukuda was the pseudonym of {{nihongo|'''Yukiari Segawa'''|瀬川 行有|Segawa Yukiari}}, born on 6 April 1917. He studied philosophy at [[Hosei University]] (Tokyo), graduating in 1940. In 1944 he was sent to [[Halmahera]]; he returned to Japan in 1946. Two years later he started teaching philosophy at his old university, where he would stay until 1970. Thereafter he supported himself by his writing.
Fukuda &mdash; the name he used as a teacher as well as a writer &mdash; was a prolific author: a ''hyōronka'' (critic or pundit) and popularizer of philosophy. He died on 11 December 2002.
== Sources == <!-- Each of the following three books has an inconspicuous English-language alternative title despite the fact that its content is entirely in Japanese. --> * ''Gendai Nihon shippitsusha daijiten'' ({{nihongo2|現代日本執筆者大事典}}) / ''Contemporary writers in Japan.'' 5 vols. Tokyo: Nichigai Associates, 1979. * ''Hyōronka jinmei-jiten'' ({{nihongo2|評論家人名事典}}) / ''Japanese critics and commentators: A biographical dictionary.'' Tokyo: Nichigai Associates, 1990. {{ISBN|4-8169-1002-6}} * ''20-seiki Nihon jinmei-jiten'' ({{nihongo2|20世紀日本人名事典}}) / ''Major 20th-century people in Japan: A biographical dictionary.'' 2 vols. Tokyo: Nichigai Associates, 2004. {{ISBN|4-8169-1853-1}}
